Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this

(14 inline comments)

Hi Kevin,

Great work in general. There are some things to fix up, noted in inline comments.

The big question, though, that I had with this patch (and the keystone integration support in general) is that I think there is some confusion as to the role that a tenant plays vs. a user. I think the two distinct concepts are kind of used for the same purpose in this code, and I think that's going to be a problem...

The tenant is basically the account that a user that has logged in belongs to. In Nova, the tenant is the *project*, which means that when Nova shares an image with another user, it will be providing the project as the tenant. However, the concept of sharing an image has to do with ownership of the image, and ownership is the purview of the *user*, not the tenant (project).

So those places in the documentation on shared images where you refer to a tenant you should really be referring to a user (the authenticated user).

Does this makes sense?

Also, Brian Waldon mentioned that he would prefer this:

GET /members/<MEMBER ID>/shared-images

to be just:

GET /shared-images/<MEMBER_ID>

What are your thoughts on that? I think I'd actually prefer GET /shared-images/<MEMBER_ID> because the /members resource is technically the purview of Keystone...

Thanks!
jay

Patch Set 2:

For clarity, I never (intentionally) refer to the _user_ in the context; the context just stores it.  I'm doing all the ownership and authorization computation/decisions based on the tenant, and yes I'm aware that maps to the project.  My thought here is that images belong to the tenant (think backup), and can be shared with other tenants (company 'foo' sells ready-made images to company 'bar').  Given this, what I've stated in the documentation hunks is correct :)

I have no problem with using 'GET /shared-images/<MEMBER ID>'; that makes plenty of sense.

Will follow-up soon with replies to your in-line comments (not sure how you managed to get it all into a single response!)

Patch Set 4:

I'll look into/fix your nits in a minute.  As for the RickH change--I accidentally did "git pull openstack master" into my branch instead of into my master.  I then switched to master, did another pull, switched back to my branch, and did a "git rebase -i master" which revealed two commits; I preserved my original commit and "fixup"'d the commit generated by the merge.  I didn't notice the commit from RickH, and there were no conflicts on this turn.  Submitting my changes was a simple "git review" with "review" aliased to "push gerrit HEAD:refs/for/master"
